Part I - Analysis of Ford GoBike System Data¶

by Aryan Talathi¶

Introduction¶

Ford GoBike is a regional public bicycle sharing system in the San Francisco Bay Area, California. This data set includes information about individual rides made in the month of February 2019 using Ford GoBike.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset is left with 174952 records of rides which have complete information of all variables. There are 16 different variables. Out of which we will be focusing on 10 for our analysis.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

Main features we are interested to analyze are:

  • Duration of bike trips
  • Number of bike trips

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The main features/factors affecting the number & duration of bike trips are:

  • Age
  • Gender
  • User Type
  • Bike Share Status
  • Time

These features will support our investigation on Duration of bike trips and Number of trips.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The variable of interest here is Duration of the trip. The distribution for duration was heavily skewed to the right. So I applied a 'log' scale transformation on the x-axis. This helped to convert the distribution to normally shapped one.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Other features we investigated were:

  • Member Age: Most of the users are between 20-60 years of age naturally. The dataset seem to have incorrect inputs about age, which is why maximum age is stretched upto 141 years. I filtered he data to show users with age below 100 years. This helped to reduce the unnecessary long tail of the distribution. Median age is at ~30 years

  • Starting Hour: This distribution is bi-modal. With peaks at 8 am and 5 pm. This may be due to the start and end of typical working hours in city of San Francisco

  • Starting Day of the week: The data is almost uniform with few ups and dows for first 5 days of the week. While on weekends the number of trips is less significantly.

  • Member Age: Most of the user base appears to be Male, about 75% whereas Females comprise of about 23% and 2% others.

  • User Type: Subscribers take most of the bike rides (90%) than Regular Customers.

  • Shared Bike Trips: A very low number of bike trips done in Feb 2019 were shared. Most of the users ride individually.

# plot matrix of numeric features against categorical features
def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    default_color = sns.color_palette()[0];
    sns.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color);

plt.figure(figsize = [15, 20]);
g = sns.PairGrid(data = df_sample, y_vars = ['duration_min', 'member_age'], 
                 x_vars = ['start_day', 'member_gender', 'user_type', 'bike_share_for_all_trip'], 
                 height = 3, aspect = 1.5);
g.map(boxgrid);
plt.show()

<Figure size 1080x1440 with 0 Axes>

Certain observations can be made from the abov plot:

  • The duration of the trip is somewhat larger at the later days of the week. And, users of all ages use the bikes across all days uniformly. thought the mean age of users on initial days of the week is slightly higher compared to later days.
  • The age group of Males and Females is almost same. Other gender people are relatively older. All the genders have same trip durations. But only some Males have duration as high as 100mins
  • Customers have significantly high trip durations compared to Subcribers. Whereas the age group of Subcribers is more than the Customers.
  • Youger people take more shared trips. Duration of both shared and unshared trips is almost same.

Plot the categorical variables against duration_min & member_age again, this time with full data and variable transforms

In [46]:
def log_trans(x, inverse = False):
    """ quick function for computing log and power operations """
    if not inverse: return np.log10(x)
    else: return np.power(10, x)

df['log_duration_min'] = df['duration_min'].apply(log_trans)
In [47]:
# plot the categorical variables against duration_min and member_age again, this time
# with full data and variable transforms
fig, ax = plt.subplots(ncols = 2, nrows = 4 , figsize = [15,10])

for i in range(len(categoric_vars)):
    var = categoric_vars[i]
    sns.violinplot(data = df, x = var, y = 'log_duration_min', ax = ax[i,0], color = dark_blue);
    ax[i,0].set_yticks(log_trans(np.array([1, 2, 5, 10, 25, 50, 100])));
    ax[i,0].set_yticklabels([1, 2, 5, 10, 25, 50, 100]);
    ax[i,0].set_ylabel('Duration (in min)')
    sns.violinplot(data = df, x = var, y = 'member_age', ax = ax[i,1], color =  dark_blue);

Observations made from above plot matrix which has data from the entire dataset.

  • Log transform has made the shape of violin-graphs more uniform and evenly distributed.
  • Bike rides during later days (weekends) of the weeks have longer durations.
  • Female users ride bikes for slightly longer duration compared to Males. And, other genders also have longer rides compared to Males.
  • Customer do longer rides than Subscribers.
  • Naturally Shared rides are somewhat shorter than non-shared rides.
  • All age members use bikes everyday of the week. Median age is around 30 for all days of the week.
  • Males have a diverse age distribution compared to Females. Other gender age distributuion is bimodal.
  • Slight difference in age distribution for Subcribers and Customers. Subscribers are a bit older than customers.
  • People who are youger take shared rides more.

Obsevations from comparison of categorical variables:

  • Saturday and Sundays have the lowest number of rides for both genders. But, for week days Females take almost the same number of rides where as Males take more rides on Thursdays.
  • For subscribers, number of rides on weekends is less than week days. But for Customers, there is no difference in no. of rides for all days.
  • The Subsriber to Customer proportion is more in Males compared to Females and Others.
  • For Males, Weekends se less rides then weekdays. But for Females this difference is very low.
  • Number of Shared rides is same throughout the week everyday. But un-shared rides follow the same trend of week days and weekend.
  • For Saturdays and Sundays, bike rides don't have any peak hours. More rides occur during mid-day hours for these days. But for weekdays, bike rides are more during peak hours.

Treating 'start_hour' as categorical variable, we find below observations:

  • At every hour of the day, Thursdays have most trips. Tuesdays have most trips at 8-9 am and 17-18pm. During the mid-day the distribution is uniform.
  • Fridays see more rides during morning hours compared to evening hours. Whereas Thursdays see more rides during evening hours compared to morning hours.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

  • Bike rides on later days of the week, Saturday and Sunday, have longer durations compared to bike rides on other weekdays.
  • Bike rides start between 7:00 AM to 7:00 PM are the longest compard to rides taken at night-time or dawn. Female bikers bike longer on average compared to male bikers.
  • Bikers with user_type 'Customer' take longer trips on average compared to bikers with user_type 'Subscriber'.
  • Bike rides that are shared have shorter duration compared to rides that are not shared.
  • Males take more rides on week days compared to weekends. Females take almost the same number of rides on week days and weekends.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

  • The Age group of Males have a diverse longer range compared to Females. More older Males take bike rides compared to older Females.
  • On average, the age of subscribers is more than customers.
  • Younger people take more shared rides.
  • For subscribers, number of rides on weekends is less than week days. But for Customers, there is no difference in no. of rides for all days.
  • Thursdays see more trips at every hour of the day. Tuesdays have most trips at 8-9 am and 17-18pm. Fridays see more rides during morning hours compared to evening hours. Whereas Thursdays see more rides during evening hours compared to morning hours.
  • Most 'Subscriber' users are male. Most 'Customer' users are also male.

def hist2dgrid_1(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating heat maps with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    palette = kwargs.pop('color');
    bins_x = np.arange(df['member_age'].min(), df['member_age'].max()+2, 2);
    bins_y = np.arange(0, 2, 0.1);
    plt.hist2d(x, y, bins = [bins_x, bins_y], cmap = palette, cmin = 0.5);
    plt.yticks(log_trans(np.array([1, 2, 5, 10, 20, 50, 100])),
              [1, 2, 5, 10, 20, 50, 100]);

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

We were able to focus on the patterns and relationships discovered in bivariate analysis with more depth wrt other variables. Moslty the features we investigated here are pretty much indenpendant from each other, and their relation doesn't have much significance. Even then, the relation between start hour and trip duration for each day of the week was pretty significant.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

  • For Subscribers, the difference between trips taken by Male and Female is more (proportionaly) than for Customers. Overall, customers take less number of rides. And most of the 'Other' gender rides are taken by customer user type.

  • Subscribers use the system heavily on work days i.e. Monday through Friday whereas customers ride a lot on weekends. Male Subscribers take trips mostly on week-days, Male customers take trips on all days. Female subsribers also take trips on all days (relatively less on weekends).

  • Duration of the rides is longer on weekends overall. For weekdays the duration is longer and more number of rides take place during the 8-10 and 15-20 hours intervals. For weekends rides are evenly distributed between 8-20 hour interval in general.

  • Younger Females take longer rides than younger Males. Whereas older Males take longer rides than older Females.

  • Customers take long duration rides. Customers are generally younger than subscribers. Subscribers vary from 18-60yrs, whereas customers vary from 18-45yrs

  • For all the 3 genders the distribution is bimodal for weekdays. Males take longer rides on Saturdays, whereas Females take longer rides on Sundays.

Conclusions¶

Some of the main conclusions derived from the analysis were:

The trip duration differs significantly with the hour of the day. The distribution here is almost a uni-modal one with a major peak in between 14th - 15th hour of the day. The duration is the least at around 2nd - 3rd hour at night. Bike rides between 8 am to 9 pm are the longest and nightime has the shortest rides. The duration of the trip is somewhat larger at the later days of the week. Most of the elderly men take rides during day-time. The age of users after 8pm to 6am is significantly lower than mid-day time. Customers have significantly high trip durations compared to Subcribers. Whereas the age group of Subcribers is more than the Customers. People who are youger take shared rides more.
